id="post-1223" class="post-1223 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-direct-action category-equality category-international-events tag-activism tag-direct-action tag-equality tag-international-events"><h2 class="entry-title"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2007/09/06/mark-your-calendars-to-stand-up/" title="Permalink to Mark Your Calendars to Stand Up" rel="bookmark">Mark Your Calendars to Stand Up</a></h2><div
class="entry-meta"> <span
class="entry-date" title="2007/09/06 11:59 am"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2007/09/06/mark-your-calendars-to-stand-up/" title="Mark Your Calendars to Stand Up" rel="bookmark">2007/09/06 11:59 am</a></span><span
class="entry-meta-sep"> / </span><span
class="entry-author author vcard"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/author/administrator/" title="by Adam Clare" rel="author">Adam Clare</a></span></div><div
class="entry-content clearfix"><p><img
src="http://i2.wp.com/farm1.static.flickr.com/101/273226069_50691dcb34.jpg?w=520" alt="woot" data-recalc-dims="1" /></p><p>Next month, October (ROCKtober) 16 and 17, to be precise, people will stand up to draw attention to international poverty. You can join millions of people from around the world to send a message to politicians that you Stand Up and Speak Out against poverty and inequality.</p><blockquote><p>In 2000, world leaders from 189 countries signed up to the Millennium Development Goals (MDGs ) &#8212; a global commitment to halve extreme poverty by 2015.</p><p>Last year, more than 23 million people in 87 countries stood up and took action to remind them of this promise. It was the largest single coordinated mobilization in the history of the Guinness World Records.</p></blockquote><div
