id="post-1206" class="post-1206 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-direct-action category-environment category-equality tag-direct-action tag-environment tag-equality tag-europe tag-money tag-usa"><h2 class="entry-title"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2007/08/15/lawsuits-champion-the-environment/" title="Permalink to Lawsuits Champion the Environment" rel="bookmark">Lawsuits Champion the Environment</a></h2><div
class="entry-meta"> <span
class="entry-date" title="2007/08/15 4:07 pm"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2007/08/15/lawsuits-champion-the-environment/" title="Lawsuits Champion the Environment" rel="bookmark">2007/08/15 4:07 pm</a></span><span
class="entry-meta-sep"> / </span><span
class="entry-author author vcard"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/author/administrator/" title="by Adam Clare" rel="author">Adam Clare</a></span></div><div
class="entry-content clearfix"><p>In the coming months many companies could face large fines from the damage that they have done to the environment. <a
href="http://www.iht.com/articles/2007/08/15/business/greencol16.php">There is a growing trend in the USA and Europe to sue those responsible for environmental damage</a> that as resulted in damage that went beyond just the environment. Confused? This example from the linked article should help you out:</p><blockquote><p>In the United States, there are currently about a dozen cases involving demands for tighter regulation and claims for damages. Among them is a case brought by property owners in Mississippi against oil and coal companies they accuse of playing a role in Hurricane Katrina, which struck the region with devastating consequences in August 2005.</p></blockquote><div
